1... Ra6! { Black takes control of the 3rd rank, and ensures that the white king cannot advance. } (1... Rd2+?? { After Ke6, the white king finds shelter from our checks. Our king will be forced away from its blockade. } 2. Ke6 Kd8 3. Rh8+ Kc7 4. Kf6 $18) 2. e6 Ra1! { Nice! Now that the pawn has pushed, we prepare to perpetually check the white king from behind. } 3. Kd6 Rd1+ 4. Ke5 Re1+ 5. Kf6 Rf1+ 6. Kg6 Rg1+ 7. Kf6 Rf1+ 8. Ke5 Re1+ { White has no choice but accept the draw by perpetual check. } *


[Event "Rook Endgames You Must Know!: The Lucena position: Building the \"bridge\""]
[Date "2021.10.10"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "?"]
[Opening "?"]
[StudyName "Rook Endgames You Must Know!"]
[ChapterName "The Lucena position: Building the \"bridge\""]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/bnboDhFM/31bASWi4"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]
[FEN "1K1k4/1P6/8/8/8/8/r7/2R5 w - - 1 1"]
[SetUp "1"]
[UTCDate "2021.10.10"]
[UTCTime "22:16:38"]

{ This is the famous Lucena position in which white will be able to queen this pawn. The crucial factors in the position are: white's king is in front of his own pawn, black's king is cut-off from the pawn by our rook, and white's rook is far away from the black king.

While my other study https://lichess.org/study/UsqmCsgC/j8DhngCd discusses it, this study will explore the variations in detail! }
1. Rd1+! { First we seek to force the black king further away from our pawn. } 1... Ke7 2. Rd4! { The all-important move. We shall see exactly why the rook belongs on the 5th rank (in this case 4th rank) in a second. } 2... Ke6 { Black cannot stop our king from reaching either c7 or a7 next move, so black waits... } 3. Kc7! { Black cannot allow us to queen next move, so must desperately attempt to find a perpetual check. } 3... Rc2+ 4. Kb6 Rb2+ 5. Kc6 (5. Kc5?? Rxb7 $10 { Don't get hasty walking your king too far up the board and accidentally abandon the pawn! }) 5... Rc2+ (5... Rb1!? { Black sees that we're not threatening to queen the pawn and can try to get creative with a waiting move. } 6. Re4+ { With the king's in opposition, why not force the black king further away before optimally positioning our rook? } 6... Kf7 7. Rc4 $18 { White has stopped any c-file checks and will play Kc7 and b8=Q next. }) 6. Kb5 Rb2+ 7. Rb4! { The bridge is complete, and the mystery behind 2. Rd4 is revealed. Our king is now safe from checks for one move, and the b pawn is queening next. } 7... Rxb4+ 8. Kxb4 Kd7 9. b8=Q $18 { White promotes and wins the game. } *


